Pellet counts were conducted annually on 5 grids of 49 1 m<sup>2</sup> permanent pellet plots. All pellets within the 1 m2 plot were counted and removed. Pellet counts were averaged annually for each grid as an index of snowshoe hare abundance.

The file 2020-03-02_hare_pellet_counts.xlsx contains all of the snowshoe hare pellet count observations from 1983 to 2019. This is the original data entry and data summary file for the Kenai National Wildlife Refuge Snowshoe Hare Grid Surveys project.","shortAbstract":"The file 2020-03-02_hare_pellet_counts.xlsx contains all of the snowshoe hare pellet count observations from 1983 to 2019.","status":["completed"],"defaultResourceLocale":{"language":"eng","characterSet":"UTF-8","country":"USA"},"supplementalInfo":"200The file HPELLETS_sum_1983_2019.xlsx was last edited by Todd Eskelin on March 2, 2020. It was renamed 2020-03-02_hare_pellet_counts.xlsx by Matt Bowser on March 17, 2020.

Data for each hare grid are contained in separate spreadsheets within the file.

It appears that data were not collected in 2001. A column named "2001 & 2002" contains counts collected in 2002 that would have been deposited by hares present on the plots between the 2000 and 2002 sampling.

Missing data are indicated by cells containing no data. These are not zeros where no pellets were observed; they indicate times when a plot could not be located and was not surveyed. The pellet counts for the following year at these plots would be counts for two years. If zero pellets were observed the following year, then it can be assumed that the missing values from previous years would have been zero.
